headline.main: THE OBSEQUIES OF GENERAL WORTH.; Address of Mayor Wood. DEDICATION OF THE WORTH MONUMENT. IMPOSING PROCESSION.

docs.lead_paragraph: The remains of the gallant and lamented Gen. WORTH were yesterday deposited under the ground upon which the Monument to his memory is to be erected, with appropriate and imposing ceremonies. They lay in state, in the Governor's room at the City Hall, during the preceding night, guarded by twenty-eight men--four from each company--of the 7lSt Regiment.

headline.main: The City Election--Local Interests and Party Politics.

docs.lead_paragraph: Mayor WOOD'S supporters do not show as much courage as he does. With characteristic self-confidence the Mayor himself declares his desire to make the contest purely personal in its character. He proclaims his readiness to moot all his accusers face to face; promises at some future day to convince the public of the purity, the unselfishness, the vigorous integrity, the public spirit and the preeminent success and brilliancy of his Administration;

headline.main: Crime in New-York--Rustic Views of City Life.

docs.lead_paragraph: To the Editor of the New-York Times: Can you tell a poor fellow, living in the country, why life is held at so cheap a rate in New-York? Now, where I live, we think a good deal of human life, and are much shocked at the frequency with which it is recklessly taken away.
